@toc main

@{b}Installing HTMLdir@{ub}

        Just copy the HTMLdir1.2 drawer where you want !

@endnode


@node methods "The two methods"
@next usage
@prev install
@toc main

@{b}The two methods@{ub}

  @{u}First method@{uu}
  Create HTML files directly in the processed directories.

  HTMLdir will create a file called @{b}hdindex.html@{ub} in each sub-directory
  of the directory you have choosen. So, an HTML file and the data it
  points out are in @{b}same directory@{ub} and, as a consequence, HTMLdir ever
  uses @{b}relative names@{ub}.

  You @{b}MUST@{ub} use this method if you want to :

    1. put the files created by HTMLdir on the net.

    2. use these files on any computer and OS.


  @{u}Second method@{uu}
  Create HTML files in a separate drawer (anywhere).

  You specify a source and a destination directory. HTMLdir processes the
  directories in the source directory and creates the HTML files in the
  destination one.

  So, with this method, HTMLdir @{b}always@{ub} use @{b}complete names@{ub} and explicitly
  use @{b}file://localhost/@{ub} in the links it generates. As a result,

    @{b}IT IS IMPOSSIBLE TO USE FILES CREATED WITH THIS METHOD ON THE NET OR
    IN ANOTHER COMPUTER OR OS.@{ub}

  But, this method can be very useful in some cases. For instance, when
  you want to process directories on a write-protected device (CDROM...)
  or when there is no space left in the source drawer.

@endnode


@node usage "Using HTMLdir from CLI"
@next examples
@prev methods
@toc main

@{b}Usage from CLI@{ub}

        Files "HTMLdir.prefs" and "deny.lst" MUST be in the same drawer that
        HTMLdir. I recommend you to cd to the HTMLdir directory to use HTMLdir
        instead of copying it in your PATH:.

        Always use complete directory names !

        The command line :

        HTMLdir directory [destination] [options]

        where:

        - directory is the directory you want to use HTMLdir on;

        - destination is the directory where the HTML files will be created.
          If you don't use a destination directory, HTML files will be created
          in the processed directory.

          If you want to create HTML files in the processed directory you MUST
          copy the "icons" drawer in it FIRST. However, the destination
          directory must exists and you have to copy the "icons" directory in
          that one.

        - options are:

          - remove : delete the created files;

          - index : create an index of the processed directory;

          - frame : display this index in a frame;

          - noinfos : don't process .info files;

          - size : sort files by size;

          - sizerev : sort files by size, reverse order;

          - date : sort files by date;

          - daterev : sort files by date, reverse order;

          - thumbs : thumbnails mode on;

          The "remove" option doesn't work if you use a destination drawer.
          "index" and "frame" can't be used at the same time. "size",
          "sizerev", "date" and "daterev" can't be used at the sametime.


        Abstract: to work properly HTMLdir needs :

          - the files deny.lst and HTMLdir.prefs in PROGDIR:

          - the "icons" drawer in the directory where the files will be
            created...



@endnode

@node examples "Examples"
@next features
@prev usage
@toc main

@{b}Examples@{ub}

        If you want to list the drawer work:tmp/images :

          >HTMLdir work:tmp/images

        You want an index of this directory :

          >HTMLdir work:tmp/images index

        You want to display this index in a frame :

          >HTMLdir work:tmp/images frame

        Now, you want to delete the files created :

          >HTMLdir work:tmp/images remove

        You want to list the files includes in CD0: in the ram:test drawer
        and create an index :

         >HTMLdir CD0: ram:test index

        You want to use thumbsnails mode and sort files by date :

         >HTMLdir CD0: ram:test index thumbs date



@endnode

@node features "Other features"
@next thumbs
@prev examples
@toc main

@{b}Other features@{ub}

        Title logo : the logo that appears at the top of the HTML pages can be
        find by default in the "icons" drawer. But, if HTMLdir finds a file
        called "logo.gif" in a directory, it will use it as a logo for that
        directory AND its subdirectories.

        Background pictures : a file background.xxx (where xxx is jpg, gif or
        png) find in the "icons" drawer is use as a background picture for all
        the directories.

        A file backframe.xxx find in the "icons" drawer is use as a background
        picture for the frame containing the index.

        Title picture : if a file called "title.jpg" is find in a directory,
        it will be use as a title picture (this picture is used instead of the
        header).

        Link page : when a file called "links.html" is find in a directory, a
        link to that page is placed at the beginning of the list.

@endnode

@node thumbs "Thumbsnails"
@next deny
@prev features
@toc main

@{b}Using thumbnails@{ub}

        When entering a new directory, HTMLdir checks if he can find a drawer
        called "thumbs". If he does, files are displayed using thumbnails
        which must be present in "thumbs".

        If a file is called filename.xxx, the corresponding thumbnails should
        have been called thumbs/t_filename.suf, where suf is the value of the
        entry suffixe_thumbs in the configuration file (default=jpg).

        For instance, if the suffixe_thumbs value is set to gif, the thumbnail
        of the file toto.mpg will be thumbs/t_toto.gif.

@endnode

@node deny "Deny file"
@next conf
@prev thumbs
@toc main

@{b}Deny file@{ub}

        Each line of "deny.lst" contains the name of a file that won't be
        processed by HTMLdir (not displayed). Good examples of such a file
        are "icons", "logo.gif" or "hdindex.html".

        When using the thumbnail mode, it's smart to add "thumbs" to that
        file to not display the thumbs drawer...

        The file MUST be terminated by the "end" line !

@endnode

@node conf "Configuration file"
@next
@prev deny
@toc main

@{b}Configuration file@{ub}

        There're two part in the configuration file. The first one allow you
        to set the values regarding the HTML tags:

        - title : title of the HTML document;

        - generator, classification and keywords : some options of the <META>
          tag;

        - text: color of the text;

        - bgcolor : color of the background;

        - link : color of the links;

        - alink : color of the active link;

        - vlink : color of the visited links;

        Second part of the configuration file concerns the HTMLdir
        preferences.

        - colortitle : color of the title text

        - completename : two possible values (0-1). 1 means that complete
          names of the directories are used as a title;

        - size : size of the title (1-6). 1 is the biggest;

        - files : HTMLdir displays the number of files and directories listed
          in the page if set to 1;

        - odd : color of the odd lines;

        - even : color of the even lines;

        - frame : size of the frame containing the index (in %);

        - maxcomplete : maximum size of the complete name of a directory.
          Useful if your screen resolution is low;

        - colorHeader : background color of the header (title) part of the
          page;

        - step_thumbs : number of thumbnails in a row;

        - suffixe_thumbs : suffixe of the thumbnails (without '.');

        Please, read the configuration file for allowed and default values.

        Colors : when you set a color, be sure that the value is correct.
        Correct values are : black, silver, gray, white, maroon, red, purple,
        fuchsia, green, lime, olive, yellow, navy, blue, teal, aqua or a
        hexedecimal representation #xxxxxx where x is in [0-9] or [a-f].
        Don't forget the '#' character !



@endnode

@node types "Filetypes"
@prev conf
@next bugs
@toc main

@{b}Filetypes@{ub}

        A filetype (suffixe) "foo" is recognized if the picture foo.xxx is
        find in the "icons" drawer, where xxx is jpg, gif or png.

        For instance, if the file txt.jpg is present in "icons", it will be
        displayed for the file Readme.txt.

        So, it's very easy to add filetypes ! Just add a new picture in the
        "icons" drawer.

        ATTENTION: HTMLdir won't work if it can't find the following files
        in the "icons" drawer :

          - home, parent, dir, dir2, index, links.
          - file, exe.

@endnode

